To establish equality for H(n), one has to show that, for any n,
there exists a height-balanced tree with height H(n).  This is
due to the relation H(n) = 1 + H(n/2) where n/2 is the integer
division.  For n odd, this is readily proved  so one can build a
tree with a top node and two sub-trees with n/2 nodes of height
H(n) - 1.  For n even, the same proof works if one first remarks
that, in that case, log(n+2) = log(n+1)  use log(n+1)  h 
  2  n + 1 and the fact that 2 is even for that.  This allows
to have a sub-tree with n/2 nodes.  For the other sub-tree with
n/2-1 nodes, one has to establish that H(n/2-1)  H(n) - 2
which is easy because, if h = H(n/2-1), then h+2  log(2n) 
log(n+1).</p>
